\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume that you want to investigate the proportion (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

) of defective items manufactured at a production line.
 Your colleague takes a random sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $30$
\end_inset

 items and tells you for each item whether or not it was defective.
 So she records the data as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=0,x_{2}=1,...,x_{n}=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 if the item is defective and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 There were three defective items in the sample.
 Assume a uniform prior for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the posterior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume your colleague only told you that there were three defective items
 in the sample of 30 items, but she did not tell you which specific items
 that were defective.
 Assume a uniform prior for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the posterior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Your colleague now tells you that she did not decide on the sample size
 before the sampling was performed.
 Her sampling plan was to keep on sampling items until she had found three
 defective ones.
 It just happened that the 
\begin_inset Formula $30$
\end_inset

th item was the third one to be defective.
 Redo the posterior calculation, under the new sampling scheme.
 Compare the results with Problem 1(a).
 [Hint: negative binomial distribution] 
\end_layout

