\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You have now managed to obtain a third sample 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1},...,z_{10}\overset{iid}{\sim}N(\theta,3)$
\end_inset

, with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}=1.221$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, the measuring device for this latter sample was defective:
 any measurement above 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 was recorded as 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 There were two such measurements.
 Compute the posterior distribution based on all three samples (
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

).
 [Hint: in this case the posterior distribution is not a known distribution
 (it is not normal for example).
 It is enough to give an expression for the (unnormalized) posterior.
 You can also plot this over a grid on your computer, if you like.]
